{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_protoss_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280656288/1908051101/0687.xml":{"full_text":"I\nTHE EVENING STAR 1\nWITH SUHDAT MOENWO EDITION. V d*7 A L W /O. Txr\n?\"\"a\" I i A^ _ aTaJ Weather.\nTto Hrtti-g 8Ut ?\"Wr 0?t?T- /'|1 fllT ^25ST\nTw0;^'oiris^i^ ^1 Tyl l|^ llilllllll I CI I\nChicago Office K.tl.Ml luk EuQliiw. B IL I J^ S M 1 M, M\n?D& SK? 1^^ f 7\" ZJ r y I \"an tonight. Tomorrow\nwirtllAit^Th'''1Suuday'\"starVt^A^nts per mouth. j tlllindcr shoWOn?.\nBy mall. nn r?,ta\n5?3S.33]|^fca* i No. 17,396. WASHINGTON, D. C., MONDAY, MAT 11, 1908?EIGHTEEN PAGES. TWO CENTS.\n2*an<Jay Stir, ooe Tear. Il.w. 7 __ 1\nSWEPT BYTORNADOES\nSections of Oklahoma Visited\nby Heavy Storm.\nSMALL TOWNS DESTROYED\nMany Persons Injured and Several\nReported Killed.\nWIRES DOWN. POINTS ISOLATED\nFour Countties Traversed by Terrific\nGale. Which Followed Oppressive\nWeather.\nWOODWARD, okla.. May 11.?A succession\nof tornadoes swept over tiie district\nlying twenty-live miles southwest,\nsouth and southeast of Woodward last\nnight. Several small isolated towns, all\nsway from the railroad and without telegraphic\ncommunication, are reported destroyed.\nmany persons have been injured\nand several are reported to have been\nkilled.\nSeven towns are reported to have suffered\ndamages more or less severe. They\nare Grand. Arnett, Vicl. Mutual. Estellc,\nCooley and Richmond. At each place\ncasualties are said to have resulted. The\nknown casualties are:\nAt Arnett?Man named Hale killed; halt\na dozen persons injured, one fatally.\nAt Vlci?Dr. Hauser, a physician, fatally\ninjured.\nAt Mutual?Arthur Sibel. Ills wife and\nseveral others seriously injured.\nGrand. the county seat of Ellis county,\nis reported to have lieen wholly wrecked.\nThe towns of Estelle and Cooley are also\nreported to have been devastated. All\nthese places are twenty-five miles from a\nrailroad. Wires are down and it is dilBi\nnit to obtain details.\nThe places where the damage is reported\nare all small. Grand is the largest\nof the seven and it lias only a few liundred\ninhabitants.\nScene of the Tornado.\nTiic scene of the tornado is the riorlli.\nest corner of the old border of Oklahoma.\nclose to the Texas and Kansas\nslate lines. As fur as learned it traversed\nfour counties and covered a distance of\nsvcnty-five miles in length. There was\njd terrific rainfall In this part of the state\nff ..^allowing oppressive weather Yesterday?\nIdeal cyclonic conditions.\nAt Little Robe, fifty-five miles southwest\nof Woodward, Mrs. J. E. Hale was\n.tilled.\nIn the vicinity of Arnett O. E. Null and\ndaughter were caught In the storm while\nlri\\ing. They escaped injury, but their\nloam was killed.\nThe little town of Cestos, Dewey county,\nalso Is reported wiped off the map. No\ndetails from there have yet been obtained.\nHard Blow at Tulsa.\nTl\"LSA. Okla., May 11.?A terrific windstorm\npassed over this part of northeast\nrn Oklahoma last night. Several houses\nwere unroofed and many small buildings\nwere blown from their foundations, plate\n.jiuss windows in Tulsa were broken and\non-hard* in the surrounding territory were\npractically devastated. No casualties are\nreported.\nEMBEZZLEMENT CHARGED.\nDavid C. Hanson of the Richmond\n(Va.) Post Office Held.\nRICHMOND. Va.. May 11.?David C.\nHanson. a confidential clerk in the Richmond\npost office and highly connected,\nwas ariested here last night, charged\nwith embezzling a numbsr of special de.iwry\nletters containing money.\nHanson was before United States Commissioner\nBrndy today and allowed ball\n.a the suig of $1,000 to answer at the\nJune term ol' the United States district\nourt.\nCHAIRMAN NEW IN CHICAGO.\nActive Preparations for Holding Big\nConvention Begun Today.\n?'1JI'.'.\\?X), May 11.?Active preparations\n\"or ihe holding of the republican national\nconvention were commenced tcday when\nUhairman New of the national committee\nopened headquarters here. Klnier Dover,\nthe secretary of the committee, and William\nl-\\ Stone, sergeant-at-arms of the\nonveir,ion. have also arrived.\nA meeting of the subcommittee on arramr<\nmeats ?n the national committee will\nfield later in tnc week, and the meinbeis\n.f t!ie local convention committee will\nalso be present.\n\"hairman New declared today tiiat the\ndemand for tickets to the convention is\nunprecedented. The reauests' are still\ntiming in at the rate of one hundred a\nday.\nIt i.- expected that within a short time\n.airmail N?-w will issue a call for a\nnesting of the national ommittee for the\np.irpose of taking up iln* delegation eon,.rt.-.\nTin- iHi.-fil?le date for this meeting\nis June I.\nThe muting of tin subcommittee in\neliarge 'if tin contention is miioliiled for\nWednemiaj anil ii is at this meeting that\nthe temporary ofli> ?rs of the convention\na ill 1\" lialiietl. Senator McVcridge. l#eslie\nM. Sl aw and Senator iJolliver arc Hie\nPandidaN whim, names have be-31 most\nt?ro:uini nily mentioned.\nSo far there have been twelve contents\nt'tl?d with Secretary l'over. but it is expected\nti.at tiiis we.-k tin- south and\nwist will add to the list. It is the\ni. c: tn.n of t\" airman N> w to hold a\nmeeting of the entire committee as soon\na> a majority of the contests have been\ntiled ttith the con. mitt'\nSOLDIER RUNS AMUCK.\nm i.-\nonoois ana i&iiis inrte and Wounds\nThree at Manila.\n;*eecial ahlritTam to The f?t?r\nMANILA. May 11.?Private Mike\nBeacham of Troop F, 1st Cavalry, ran\namuck in the barracks at Camp Stotsenhurg\nthis afternoon. He shot and killed\nFirst Sergt. W illiam lloey and Privates\nThomas F. Woodward and U. Wilson, and\nwounded l*rivates Kdward F. Clark. Fmmet\nW. Sain peer and Harry W. Whipple.\nClark's wound is in the head and is\nserious, lie may die of it.\nBeacham was captured and placed in\nclose eonltnemeni. He is believed to I*\ninsane. A full report of the tragedy has\nnot been received yet. The killed and\nwounded arc all members of Troop F.\nRAY NER TAKES ACTION\nI Proposes Court of Inquiry ir\nthe Stewart Case.\ni\nI WILL SPEAK TOMORROW\n\nj Resolution Lies Upon the Senatt\nTable.\ni RIGHTS OF THE EXECUTIVI\n\nI\nMaryland Senator May Make Public\nthe Letter Becently Sent to Him\nby the President.\nSenator Ruyner today introduced a reso\ni lution \"authorizing tho President to eon\nvene a court of inquiry.\" to eons'st o\nfive officers of the army, to investigat'\ncharges and accusations against Col. \\\\\"i!\nliarr. F. Stewart of the army, who ha\nj been detailed to serve until retirenn-n\nat the abandoned military post of For\nGrant, Ariz. The resolution will lie 01\nthe table until tomorrow, when Mr. Ray\nner will speak upon it. lie gave notici\nthat lie expected the Senate to take actioi\nat that time.\nThe Col. Stewart ease is one of tin\nsubjects discussed by President Roosevel\nin his recent letters to Senator Raynei\nand Senator Stewart of Vermont, declaring\nthat as eonimarider-tn-ehlef rh<\nPresident is supreme In all matters pep\ni laining to the army and navy.\nThe resolution by Senator Rayner de\nclares in the preamble that charges un<\naccusations have been tiled with tin\nPresident of the United States affectirq\nthe qualifications and status of Col. Stew\n1 art as an officer and that lie had not beei\nserved with a copy of the charge^. It i:\npointed out that the officer on two occasions\nhas asked for a court of inquiry\nand that his requests have been denied\nand that in- has been without opportunity\nto defend himself against ttie \"ex parte\naccusations\" on which lie was assigned t<\na deserted post at Fort Grant, Ariz., v. thou!\ncommand, later transferred to a post\nwithout command at St. Augustine, Fla.,\nand recently ordered back to Fort Grant\nIt is declared that this \"punishment\"\naas b^en inflicted without Col. Stewart\nhaving been afforded the slightest opportunity\nto secure information concerning\nthe charges. The resolution if adopted\nwould compel the War Department to pro\nduce all of the charges and accusation*\non file at the department and with President\nRoosevelt. The officer would have\nthe authority to confront his accusers and\nto be represented at the court with counsel.\nMr. Bayner's Intention.\nIn addressing the Senate tomorrow\nSenator Rayner does not Intend to discuss\nthe question whether Col. Stewart\nhas merited punishment.\" lie will tontine\nhis argument to the question o!\nwhether the President has the right to\ncondemn an officer to punishment without\n^he court of inquiry guaranteed to\nevery officer by the articles of war. It\nis not the senator's intention to make\npublic the letter which he received front\nthe President, unless it is contended by\nsenators opposing the demand for a court\nthat the President is entirely within his\nrights to \"detail'' an officer of the army\nto whatever post he pleases, and' that\nI such a detail does not technically const l1\ntute \"punishment.\"\nIn such event it is expected Senator\nKayner will offer the President's letter in\nreply. That letter, it is said, in several\ninstances declares that tin officer merited\nthe \"punishment\" bestowed, and\nshows that the President himself regards\nStewart's exile as in the nature of \"punishment.\"\nMr. Foraker's Purpose.\nThe point raised by Mr. Kayner regarding\nthe President's authority will i>\npressed by Mr. Foraker when lie takes\nup the Brownsville case. Xo opportunity\nhad been afforded Senator Foraker\ntb bring before the Senate his bill for tut\nre-eidistrncnt of the colored soldiers discharged\nwithout honor as a result of the\nBrownsville affair, up to the time The\nStar went to press today. Consideration\nof the agricultural appropriation bill will\nb-- continued by order of the Senate until\n4 o'clock this afternoon, when a vote on\nI that bill will be taken. Then, in aeI\noordance with his announcement, made\nI Saturday. Mr. Foraker will at once call\n1 up his Brownsville bill, unless the posl\noffice appropriatioi bill, now pending,\nshould intervene.\nInterest was added io the tense situation\nat the Senate end of the Capitol\ntoday on account of the fact that thf\n1 President has not yet intimated tliat Ik\nwill make public all or any of the letters\nwhich he has written recently to senui\ntors, asserting his supremacy in the conj\ntrul of the army and navy. It was thought\nthat he might have something to say oi:\nthe matter soon after he returned last\nnight from Pine Knot, Va. I.i. is underi\nctn. tV<eii Yf r T?Aro l/t?r i nntr?? rlg?t\nUIVVU JL 1 4 Cfc L *fU X V ...v. -w a\nmined\" than ever to bring tliese lei ten\nto the attention of the Senate publicly\nwith u view to criticising the President\nfor alleged interference with the legislu;\ntire branch of the government. Ol\nj our.-e Mr. I'oraker's principal effort will\nt be to show tliut as the 1 'resident lias\nagain asserted his belief in the guilt\nI the eolored soldiers and gone so far a|\nto deny the authority of Congress to in;\nterfere In any way in what he has dom\nwith reference to them, it would be ridiculous\nto pass a bill making the President\nthe judge as to the rights of tin\nsoldiers to re-enlist, as is provided in\nSenator Warner's Villi. The debate wil1\nthen iiinge, it is said, on the extent\nthe President's authority as commanderI\nin-cldef of the army.\nI Mr. Koraker is expected to make all\nI tin capital possible out of the Stewart\n1 us e.\nHurled Her Children Out of Window\n'lllCAdO. May 11.? Mrs. Km ma ],ofj\ngren liurled her children. Arthur, thre?.\nI years old. and Juliu, six months, from tin\nj second-story w indow of her home lasl\ni night, injuring both so'severely that they\nnrobablv will die. The habv suffered\nI\nfractured skull and botli of its arms wert\nbroken. Arthur was Internally injured,\nand liis left leg and one arm were broken,\nj Mrs. l.ofgren hail been sick, and it is bej\nlleved she V?eouine suddenly insatie. Both\nchildren arc said to have been asleej\nwhen she lifted them from their beds\nand threw them to the sidewalk.\ne *Yaquis\nMay Quit Fighting.\nThere is promise of a cessation of tin\nlong-continued strife between .the Mex\nican government and the Ya<jul Indium\nIf the peace measures .now under way an\nbrought to a successful conclusion. Re\ncently there has been a gathering of th<\nIndians at Bacatete, when they agreed t?\ni accept conditions and privileges extender\nto them by the government and at tin\nsame lime deliver up their arms aru\nammunition.\ni\nI\nI\n\nI\ni\ni\n\ni\nMR. BR1\nFLEET FESTIVITIES\ni t\n;j\njSan Francisco Begins Second\n\nWeek of Carnival.\nSIGHTSEEING FOR OFFICERS\nI\nBase Ball Games for Army and Navy\nChampionship.\nEVANS* JOURNEY EASTWARD\n-1\n.1\nReceptions Planned for Him at\nPoints Along the Way?Cordial\ni\nGreeting in Utah.\nM SAX FRANCISCO, May 11.?Although\nthe sky was overcast with clouds u'ld the\nwind portended rain, the second week's!\nentertainment of the officers and men of i\nj tin- tl.-et bewail tnis morning promptly\naccording to program. Beginning at h\no'clock and continuing at intervals\nthroughout the day. big observation ears\nj left the terminus at the ferry building,\nand, proceeding over the network of the\nlines of the I'nited Railroads, passed near- j\nly every point of interest in the city and\nsuburbs on the peninsula. These excur:\nsious were arranged for the benefit of the j\n1 sailors.\nI\nJ At 0 o'clock l.oo warrant ollicers were.\ntaken across the bay to Marin county,\nj and thence by the winding railway to ti e\nsummit of Mount Tamalpaia. which com- I\nI mands a splendid view of sea and shore\n1 to.- hundreds of miles. Ati hour later i\nSecretary Metealf and about -kiu fleet otti1\neers were takot in automobiles through\nj the city and to several picturesque counI\ntrj places. i\nTiie preliminary contests of tlie army and\ni navy championship bast; ball games were-\nbegun at Z o'clock on the Presidio grounds\nand were witnessed by a large attendance\nj of spectators. L?uring tlie afternoon\nth< re were band concerts in the various\ni parks, wliich were repeated in the eveni\ning.\nj A iiurnocv of 1'aciiic coast amateur box- j\nI ing contest will bo a feature of tlie\ni i night's entertainment which will culmi,\nnatc in the second reception of. Secretary\nt Metealf and the officers of the ilect. This\nwill l.e laid at the Fairrnount Hotel.\nRear Admiral Thomas, who contracted\nt st ci.t.l Ssstt m-ilsi v Mini Was obliged to re\ni; rnain in )ii apartments at tli* alrniount\n?j llotei in-aily all du> yesterday, was\njgreatly improved this morning. and at. an\nearly hour went on hoard the flagship\nConnecticut,\nEVANS REACHES OGDEN.\nGreeted by Delegation of State Of!'!\nficials?Address to Crowd.\n?>e;i >i:NT, 1 tali. May It.?Hear Admiral\nRobley D. Evans, en route east, was re'\necived at the Union depot at 8 o'clock\nthis morning by several hundred persons,\nj Including a delegation of state officials\nlau l others from Salt T.ake City. His car\nwas opened tlo Acting tio\\. I iuge\\ and\nI staff, veterans of the G. A. K. and friends,\nwho sent in personal cards, !>nt. the doors\ni were soon closed on the advice of his\nJ physician-\nCater the admiral, on crutches, made Ins\nway to the rear platform and addressed\nthe crowd, expressing his appreciation of\nthe honor shown him by the people of\njjjjj, .state, lie recalled how he had been\nsent as Utah's cadet to Annapolis and\nsaid he owed a debt of gratitude to Utah.\nThen, selecting a bunch of sweet peas\nfrom the bounteous floral offering of Cal1\nifornia. he presented the flowers to rf llt>\ntie girl in front of him and returned to\nhis berth in the ear.\nUTAH TO GREET EVANS.\ns Officialdom to Preseut the Admiral\nWith a Memorial.\nJ j salt lake city. Utah, May 11.'\ni Utah officialdom, in a special car, will\nleave Salt laike today to greet Admiral\nRobley P. Evans during his brief stay in\nj' Ogden and present hini with a memorial.\nThe delegation will include Acting Gov.\n1 C. H Tingev. the governor's staff, ofi\nfleer-! front Uotl Douglas garrison and the\n\n[AX'S IDEA OF THE OPl'US,\n11\nfederal officials in Suit Lake and all elec- j I\ntive officers of the state. 1\nThe admiral is regarded as a protege I\nof Utah, since it was from this common- i I\nwealth, then a territory, that he was ap-\npointed to the 'Annapolis Naval Academy.\n2,000 Cheered at Reno. i\nRKNA, Nev.. May 11.-While Rear Ad-!'\nnilral lDvans' car, the Sunset, waited at j\nthe Southern Pacific station yesterday\nmore than 15,000 Reno people stood at\nme piatmrm ana cneereu ine veteran. i\nllu acknowledged the greeting by raising L\nthe curtain and bowing his thanks. I\nMartin GUilbert, who was with him;\ntwenty-one years ago on the Yorktown,\nwas recognized. \"Hullo. Martin, what j\nyou doing here?\" said Admiral Evans, j\nwhen the suilor approaclied him. Then I\nthey talked of old days?boxing together\non the old gunboat, the Chilean incident\nand rheumatism, which afflicted both.\n\"Time makes great changes.\" said Ad- ;p\nmiral Evans grimly, us the trait) pulled\nout.\nPlanning Australian Welcome.\nMELBOURNE. May 11.?Alfred Deakin,\nprime minister of Australia, has asked the\ncommittee, composed of members of both\nfederal houses, to consult with the pre-\nmler.-i of New South Wales and Victoria\nregarding the welcome to be extended 011\nthe arrival of the American fleet of battle- i\nships. It is officially announced that the\nfleet is scheduled to arrive at Sydney i I\nAugust 2n and Melbourne August LI). The a\nfleet will leave Austral an waters Sep- jtemher\n3.\n_ a\nCUBAN OFFICERS HERE j i\nS\nt!\nWILL INSPECT THE AMERICAN j s\nMILITARY POSTS. j J\ng\nli\ntteii. I'mo Lruerra, commander ol the j\nCuban anny; Maj. Marti, son of the\nCuban patriot of that name, and Capt. j u\nLanda. commander of the machine gun e\nbattery of th? Cuban army, who are inak-\ning an official tour of inspection of the I\nmilitary posts of the United States, are j\nnow in this city. They visited the War s\nDepartment this morning and paid their j,\nrespects to Acting Secretary Oliver and\nGen. Deli, chief of staff, and were as-\nsured that they should have every facility n\nto study the organization and methods p\nof the United States Army.\nGon. Guorri: and his military compun-j u\nions will spend two months tinder;\ninstruction at the officers' school at Fort'\nI.euvcnwurth, Kan., after wliich tliey will 1\nattend the maneuvers of the French and tJ\nGerman armies. It Is intended that they j\nI shall return to Cuba in October next and j 11\nbegin recruiting for the Cuban army,\nI which it is designed to have organized a\nin time for the re-establishment of the'\nCuban republic in February mext.\nFOREST RESERVE RECEIPTS.\nFulton Amendment to Agricultural;\nBill Debated.\nThe agricultural appropriation lull was'\ntaken up by tie Senate today shortly aft-\ni e r *11 o'clock In accordance with an agree- j\nmerit by the Senate Saturday that it i\nI\nmeasure should be voted on before ad-\nI journnient today. I n\nSenator Fulton of Oregon moved an\namendment that hereafter 25 per cent t;\nI of all money received anuiially from for1\nest reserves shall, be paid to the\nstates or territories .in which the 1 v\nreserves are .located to be expended I\nas the legislatures shall direct for the' s\npublic Schools or public roads of the!.'\ncounties in which the reserves are sit- )j\nuated. In the past only 10 per cent of!v\nthese funds has been thus distributed.\nI Opposition to the amendment was made j11\nby Senator Heyburn of Idaho, who in- j\ni sisted that the constitution of his states*!\ni provides that all money received from the j r*\nforest reserves shall go to the school fund j\nof the state.\nQuestioning the light of Congress to\nappropriate money for the development\ni of the forest reserves and then turning j\nI over 25 per cent of the income of such\ninvestments to states in which tliey hap;\npen to be located. Senator Bacon declared\nI that that principle was not applied to any\nother function of the government. He\nargued that as the forest reserves belong P\nto the nation the income from them t\nshould belong to the nation. t\nI t\nWorld Auto Racers Leave Tokio.\nTOKIO. May 11.?The American com-1\nj petttors in the New York-Paris automo- 1\nj bile race arrived here yesterday, and left 1 y\nTokio this morning on their way to'\nVladivostok. Here all the cars will meet i f\nand make a new start. The American s\ncontestants say they are 1,200 miles in I\nthe lead. j d\n\nITION.\n10 ONEJPPOSEfl IT\nInti-Betting Bill Ready for\nSignature.\n10USE FAVORABLY ACTS\nLgrees to Senate Amendment to the\nMeasure.\nBACTICALLY UNANIMOUS VOTE\nWashington Jockey Club Will Build\na New Track and Grandstand\nAcross the Maryland Line.\nBy a unanimous viva voce vote the\nlouse of Representatives today took tinal\nI.B1 S J-.l..?\nciiuii Mii luc uia i vi lut: iiitrivi\ntenuiiig road, which, from the Sims\nluendnumt. has come (o be known as the\nuli-gambling bill. Immediately after the\nlouse met this morning the bill with\nenate amendment, was called up from\nlie Speaker's table by Representative\nnilth of Michigan, chairman of tlie\nlouse District committee. Representative\nims of Tennessee, author of the unttambling\namendment, demanded a second\n!i order that any members desiring to\nIscuss tlie bill might have the opporunity\nduring tlie forty minutes allowed\nnder this arrangement. Hut nobody\nare'l to talk.\nThe fact that the bill has lair, on the\nSpeaker's tfible for several weeks nouraged\nits opponents in the belief that\n[Othing would be done with it at this\nesston, but today's action dissipated that\nlope.\nTlie tistuil roll call was .avoided. Mr.\nVilliams (Miss.), th<? minority leader, renarked\nthat inasmuch as it was a me:Lorous\nmeasure he would not Insist on\nroll cail. The vot? practically was\ninanimous.\nThe New Law.\nFollowing is tlie text of the gambling\nuovision as now accepted by both\nlouses:\n\"it shall be unlawful for fiuj person or\nssociatlun of persons to bet, gamble or\ntiake books or pools on tlie result of any\nmtting or running race of horses, or\noat race, or race of tiny kind, or on any\nlection, or any contest of any kind, or\n;amc of base ball. person or assoiu'ion\nof persons violating the provisions\nf this section shall be lined not cxccedug\nlive hundred dollars, or imprisoned\nlot uiore than ninety days, or both.\"\nNew Track in Maryland.\nOne of tlie officials of tie- Washington\noekoy cllub, who was at the Capitol this\nlorning to watch the bill go through,\nlade the following statement:\n\"The Jockey Club made no light against\nhis bill, as we preferred to race wliero\niiere <-onId b<? no objection, and where we\ncould encounter more liberal laws. We\nropose to build :i new track and grandtand\nright across the District line, and\nuse the old track and stables for trairiig\npurposes. The change will not inconenienee\nthe public, as the old track Is\ner> near the District line, and tlie enrance\nto the new track will bo not over\nflve-minute ride on the electric cars\nrom the old entrance. It is also probable\nhat in the future the meetings here will\ne for a longer period than in the past.\"\nCLEVELAND \"iMPBOVING.\nfriends Think He Will Return to\nPrinceton This Week.\nLAKEWOOD, N. J., May 11.?(Jrover\nlleveland's condition continues to imrove.\nso it is said at the Lakewood Hoel.\nThe ex-President's friends here think\nhat lie will be taken to Ills home in\n'riueeton within the week.\nMrs. Cle\\ eland attended service in the\n'resbyterian Church yesterday, and after\nhut t'Kik a short walk about town before\ne.turuing to the hotel. She was also out\ncalking in the afternoon.\nThe Cleveland rooms in the hotel are\null of (lowers and plants which have been\nent by friends of the family who live In\n^akewood. Dr. Bryant spent the entire\niuy at the hotel.\nft\n;IN SINCERE ACCORD'\n\nPresident Welcomes Prosperity\nAssociation Committee.\nI\nPROMISES HIS CORDIAL AID\nI\nSays Standard of Business Honestyi j\nIs Higher Than Ever.\ni ;i\nSEQUEL TO WAR ON ABUSES\nt\nj Industrial Depression and Stagnation\nj Caused, He Declares, by Shocking j\nT7 nrrnl o f A V aft* A/la\nvviattvua ui jacvuuuo?\n\nA committer from the National Pros-.\nperity Association of St. J.ouis called on\nPresident Roosevelt today to urge Ids aid\nIn furthering tlieir plans for encouraging\nthe return of prosperity throughout the j\ncountry. The committee found the Presi- t\ndent cordial in his treatment und frank1 c\n(in his expressions of willingness to aid;\nthem In every way possible. A short: i\nspeech was ntadc by E. C\". Simmons, j 1\nchairman of the executive committee of t\nI the association, which was responded to 1\nI by the President. Other members of the j c\ncommittee were F. J. Wade. Fid ward I>e- j\nvoy. F. H. Wlberg. J. E. Smith, W. K. j 1\nBixby, Murray Carleton, George A. Meyer\nand Jackson Jcdinson. t\nThe President responded as follows: 1\nThe President's Response. 1\nThe President responded as follows:\n\"I am in hearty sympathy with the\navowed object of the National Prosperity J\nAssociation. It is excellent. We have\ngone far in uprooting abuses which\nthreaten our national life. Taken as a\nwhole, the standard of honesty in our\nbusiness life has been high, and today the i\nstandard is, I believe, beyond what it\nhas ever been, and this largely because j\nwe have made determined war on the 1\nabuses that lowered it. As you have\nj said, the depression and stagnation from\nt which our country is now happily be- I,\n1 ginning to recover were not caused by re- i\nform legislation, but by the revelation t\nI of shocking conditions in certain of our\ni corporations by reckless operations Hi\nI high finance, by calamity and by certain\ni striking, though. I believe, exceptional. J\ni Instances of business and civic dlshon- i j\nesty. Of course, all good men must\nagree with you In your condemnation of i\nunwise agitation. The apathetic accep- i\ntance of abuses in our governmental and\nI business administrations Is no more dan|\ngerous than the demagogic appeals of\nprofessional agitators to class hatreds.\nOur national conscience. I lirnily believe,'\nhas been awakened. We w ill not and can- 1\ni not go back to the conditions which tol-\nerated wrongdoing. Neither can we j\nafford to be led astray by those who!.\nwould embark us In a visionary and twist- 1\ni ed crusade against all corporations, all\nj business methods. We should address i\nourselves to the faithful and honest ob-\nservanee of the laws of civic righteous- j'\nness. l\n\"The welfare of all of us can best be I\ni obtained by striving for a policy which I\nwill promote the welfare of each of us. 11\n\\W must ill f-n-nrxTMf 1. l?i nnli>r thnt Vn'Ti. i\nerlt may be derived by the entire nut Ion.\nj Go Ad laws make for good government;\nbut laws sire of no avail unless vitalized\nby the people who made them. Our recent\nlegislation lists been good, and it is j\nto the Interest of the entire country, and\nespecially of the business interests, that\nit should be enforced. Such further rogu- j\nlatory legislation as is required is merely\nI a building upon the broad foundations j\nthat have been laid. It conceals no menj\nace to business, any more than that legts|\nlation which has already been enacted.\nThere is no need for agitation concerning\nit; there is 110 excuse for demagogic\nexcitement about it. It is as much our\nduty to conserve the real rights of properly\nas It is to conserve the real rights!\n01' labor. This we have done in the past,\nand tills we ought to do, and will do, in\nthe future.\"\nResolution of Confidence.\n\"The country realizes that confidence is j\nnot a matter of law. It is an intangible j\nsomething which exists in the relations of}\nmen. These relations have been strengthened\nin our own countiy by the economic\nreforms that have been Instituted. Thcrfefore\nwe are more powerful today than we j\nhave ever been. So far as the present ad-\nministration is concerned, it will continue i\nunchanged the i?olicy of safeguarding the!\nrights of all and of embracing every possible\nami legitimate means to advance the j\nwelfare and prosperity of our country.\n\"L?ct there be no misunderstanding:\nabout this. The business and commercial\nInterests of this country to be prosperous\nin any enduring sense must be administered\nhonestly. With occasional exceptions\nthey have been and arc now so ad-'\nI ministered. As you have well said, 1\nwherever there is evidence of dishonesty j\nit must be pursued relentlessly and pun- j\nished: but having thus moved forwaid to'\na high plane of business integrity, and 011!\nthat plane built wisely, let 110 mean seize\nthe moment, when we have as a nation\npillorlzcd the real malefactors, to say that\nj till Alii*'! trail jJuniiicrT iiivii, yjl auj 1\nconsiderable number of them, are male- I 1\nj factors. I welcome your work and shall 1\nbe glad to co-operate with you in any\nj effort to establish prosperity on right ur;d i 1\ni honest lines.\"\nCONGRES OF FISHERIES. j\nl\nInternational Meeting- to Be Held\nHere in September.\nIn accordance with the decision of the\nthird international fishery congress, which\nj met at Vienna, In 190f>, the fourth con- 1\nj gress will be held in this city September\nj i?l to September US. under the auspices\nI of the United States bureau of fisheries\ni and tire American Fisheries Society. National,\nstate and provincial governments,\nsocieties, associations, clubs and other i\nticdles' interested have been invited to\nnominate and send delegates. The object i\nof the congress Is to deliberate on all\nImportant affairs concerning fishing and\nfish culture, and to submit propositions\nand memorials to governments and to\nprovincial and local authorities.\nThe membership of the congress will\nconsist of government, state and provln-\nelal representatives: delegates from home\nand foreign societies; corporations and j t\npersonages invited by the management of j\nthe congress, and persons at home and t\nabroad who are deemed to have an inter- j\nest in the purposes of the congress and f\nexpress a wish to take part in It.\nThe president and the secretary general i\nof the fourth congress will be nominated 1\nby the United States bureau of fisheries.\nAmong the subjects that are likely to be\nI discussed are: Commercial fisheries, mat\ni ters affecting the fisherman and the fish- 1\ning population, legislation and regulations\naffecting fishing, fish culture and the ol?- j\nstruction and pollution of waters. Inter- t\nnational matters affecting fisheries, agri- 11\nculture, acclimatization, fish-ways and I\nfish-ladders, biological investigation of 1\nwaters and their Inhabitants, diseases and 1\nparasites, angling and sport fishing. 11\nLAPOflTE TRAGEDY\nBAFflKJFFICERS\n:urther Excavations for\nBodies Postponed by Sheriff.\nDELAYED BY THE CURIOUS\nEstimated 15.000 Persons Visited\nGrounds Yesterday.\nCHE ATTITUDE OF THE DEFENSE\n[mpression That Mrs. Gunness Is\nStill Alive Widepspead?Strange\nFind With Helgelein's Body.\nIjAPORTK. Ind.. May 11 ?Picking wn\nhe rhrcdr' of the evidence tending to\nunneet Ray f*aniphere with the ?le.i!\n?f Mrs. UunnePK and li?r three children,\nind iteihaps also of Andrew lloigetein, N\n:lie main purpose of the author.ties he?\noday. Whether search f<?r more hod it\nwill be pronecuted has not U-t-n tlnally\nletermined. Sheriff Sniutzer Indicating\nr. tf lt.tt ft ltne -n i o.r\n\"V*-1 wuj I irni l ui liiri At n iiuii^ 111,.j\n>e postponed until tomorrow*.\nThe sheriff has found difficulty :n car yinjf\non this work beoati.-e ot flic motjidly\ncurious persons who have tlock< d\no the place where ten corpses were discovered\nlust week. FYiday the exeaxat\nftp In the barnyard was liindered. and\nSaturday it was halted, b> th<- crowds I:\ns expected, however, that the number of\nvisitors will be lessened today, some l.Y*10\npersons bavin*- inspected the gro